[Google Chrome Super Sync Sports](http://www.google.com/chrome/supersyncsports/)<br>

I have an interesting example of a very minimalistic and analog example of gamification (just to show that while digital certainly has more stroke, analog can be valuable and very simple). Our catering company has introduced a competition in the company canteen, which is called "Beat the alarm clock". The principle is that they have an i-Phone sitting at the check-out till with an alarm set to a time during lunch break, which is not known or visible. And whoever is at the till when the alarm goes off, gets his meal for free. A nice way to encourage people to eat in the cafeteria, but also lighten the mood in the waiting queue, and without much effort. I found that a nice case study.

In the UK, Green Sheild stamps were one of the first 'loyalty' techniques, and there is discussion on this public wiki page about how Tesco, a large supermarket, built upon it
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Shield_Stamps

Other examples are toys 'collect the set' from either McDonalds/Kellogs
